The concept of a standard basis isn't confined to numerical coordinate spaces. It can be defined for other [vector spaces](/Vector_space) whose elements are characterized by [coefficients](/Coefficient), such as [polynomials](/Polynomial) and [matrices](/Matrix_(mathematics)). In these contexts, the standard basis is formed by elements where only one coefficient is non-zero (and that coefficient is 1), while all others are zero.

For the vector space of polynomials, the standard basis is often referred to as the [monomial basis](/Monomial_basis). This basis consists of the simplest polynomial building blocks: the monomials. For example, in a space of polynomials up to degree 2, the standard basis might be {1, x, x²}.

In the case of matrices, specifically m × n matrices, the standard basis is comprised of matrices that contain a single '1' in one position and zeros everywhere else. For instance, consider the standard basis for 2×2 matrices:










