### Properties

By its very definition, the standard basis possesses a crucial set of properties. It is a [sequence](/Sequence) of vectors that are not only [orthogonal](/Orthogonal) to each other (meaning their dot product is zero, indicating they are perpendicular) but also [unit vectors](/Unit_vectors) (meaning they each have a length or magnitude of 1). Consequently, the standard basis is always an [ordered](/Ordered_basis) and [orthonormal](/Orthonormal_basis) basis. This combination of properties makes it exceptionally well-behaved and easy to work with.

However, it's important to note that simply being an ordered orthonormal basis does not automatically make it a standard basis. Consider, for example, a rotated coordinate system in 2D. The vectors representing a 30° rotation of the standard basis in the [Cartesian coordinate system](/Cartesian_coordinate_system) might be:









